text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 15px; line-height: normal; font-family: Georgia; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: --> Probability is a way of describing uncertainty in numerical terms.

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 25px; line-height: normal; font-family: Georgia; cursor: pointer; fill-opacity: 1;

-webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 15px; line-height: normal; font-family: Georgia; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: --> A probability experiment, also called a random experiment, is an experiment for which the result, or outcome,

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 15px; line-height: normal; font-family: Georgia; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: -->The set of all possible outcomes of a random experiment is called the SAMPLE SPACE, and any particular set
of outcomes is called an EVENT.

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 15px; line-height: normal; font-family: Georgia; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: For example, consider a cube with faces numbered 1 to 6, called a 6-sided die.

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 15px; line-height: normal; font-family: Georgia; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: Rolling the die once is an experiment in which there are 6 possible outcomes—either 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, or 6
will appear on the top face

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 15px; line-height: normal; font-family: Georgia; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: The SAMPLE SPACE for this experiment is the set of numbers 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 15px; line-height: normal; font-family: Georgia; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: Two examples of EVENTS for this experiment are (i) rolling the number 2, which has only one outcome,
and (ii) rolling an odd number, which has three outcomes.[1,3,5]

text.style: -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 15px; line-height: normal; font-family: Georgia; cursor: pointer;

-webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); text-anchor: middle; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 15px; line-height: normal; font-family: Georgia; cursor: pointer;
text.tspan: The probability of an event is a number from 0 to 1, inclusive, that indicates the likelihood that the event occurs
when the experiment is performed.The greater the number, the more likely the event.
